<h2>Data Source and Methodology</h2>
<p>All calculations are strictly based on the formulas and data provided by authoritative surveying guidelines. For further details, refer to <a href="https://www.example.com" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Surveying Standards</a>.</p>
</section>
<section class="content-section formula">
<h2>The Formula Explained</h2>
<p>The conversion between azimuth and bearing involves specific trigonometric calculations:</p>
<div class="formula-box">
<p>Azimuth to Bearing: <code>Bearing = (Azimuth + 180) % 360</code></p>
<p>Bearing to Azimuth: <code>Azimuth = (Bearing - 180) % 360</code></p>
</div>
</section>
<section class="content-section glossary">
<h2>Glossary of Terms</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Azimuth:</strong> A horizontal angle measured clockwise from a north base line.</li>
<li><strong>Bearing:</strong> The angle between the reference direction (north or south) and a line.</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section class="content-section example">
<h2>How It Works: A Step-by-Step Example</h2>
<p>Let's say you have an azimuth of 120 degrees. To convert this to a bearing, you would use the formula: <code>Bearing = (120 + 180) % 360 = 300</code>. Thus, the bearing is 300 degrees.</p>
</section>
<section class="content-section faq-section">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>
<dl>
<dt>What is an Azimuth?</dt>
<dd>An azimuth is a direction expressed as the angular distance from a reference direction, typically north.</dd>
<dt>How is a Bearing different from an Azimuth?</dt>
<dd>A bearing is the angle between a line and a reference direction, usually north or south.</dd>
<dt>Why convert between Azimuth and Bearing?</dt>
<dd>Conversion is essential in surveying to interpret directional data accurately for navigation and mapping.</dd>
<dt>How accurate are these conversions?</dt>
<dd>The conversions are highly accurate as they are based on standard surveying calculations.</dd>
<dt>Can this tool be used for navigation?</dt>
<dd>Yes, it can be used for navigational purposes where precise direction measurements are required.</dd>
</dl>
